data.content:
## What Breaks in .NET 11

In EF Core 11, the **sync-over-async opt-in for the Cosmos DB provider is removed entirely**. The escape hatch you configured in .NET 10 (e.g., `EnableSyncOverAsync()`) no longer exists.

Every synchronous call in your repository — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, `SaveChanges()` — will throw an **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime with no way to suppress it.

## The Fix

You must convert to async APIs:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types → `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods → `async` + `Async` suffix by convention
- LINQ terminals → `ToListAsync()`, `FirstAsync()`, `CountAsync()`
- `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
- `Add()` stays synchronous (it's an in-memory operation, no I/O)

This will ripple up your call stack — all callers must also become async (`async`/`await` all the way up).
